            <div class="story-text">
                <p>Maria <strong>discovered</strong> postcrossing last year when her friend told her about it. She <strong>had never heard</strong> of this project before, but it sounded very interesting.</p>
                
                <p>First, Maria <strong>registered</strong> on the postcrossing website. She <strong>filled</strong> in her address and <strong>read</strong> all the instructions carefully. Then she <strong>requested</strong> her first address ‚Äì it was for a person in Japan!</p>
                
                <p>Maria <strong>went</strong> to the local shop and <strong>bought</strong> a beautiful postcard with a picture of her city. She <strong>wrote</strong> a friendly message: "Hello from Germany! I hope you like this postcard. This is my first postcrossing experience!" She <strong>didn't forget</strong> to write the Postcard ID: JP-54321.</p>
                
                <p>The next day, Maria <strong>walked</strong> to the post office and <strong>sent</strong> the postcard. She <strong>felt</strong> very excited about her new hobby.</p>
                
                <p>Three weeks later, something amazing <strong>happened</strong>. Maria <strong>opened</strong> her mailbox and <strong>found</strong> a colorful postcard from Brazil! She <strong>had never received</strong> mail from South America before. The postcard <strong>showed</strong> a beautiful beach, and the sender <strong>wrote</strong> about the weather and local food.</p>
                
                <p>Since then, Maria <strong>has sent</strong> postcards to fifteen different countries. She <strong>has received</strong> postcards from places she <strong>had never heard</strong> of before ‚Äì like Tasmania, Estonia, and Madagascar. Her postcrossing collection <strong>has grown</strong> to twenty-three postcards from around the world.</p>
                
                <p>Last month, Maria <strong>got</strong> her most special postcard. It <strong>came</strong> from a small village in Nepal. The sender <strong>drew</strong> a picture of mountains and <strong>wrote</strong> about life in the Himalayas. Maria <strong>has kept</strong> this postcard on her desk because it's so unique.</p>
                
                <p><strong>Have you ever tried</strong> postcrossing? Maria <strong>has made</strong> many friends through this project, and she <strong>has learned</strong> about different cultures. She <strong>plans</strong> to continue this hobby for many years!</p>
            </div>
